<hint name="helpSection"><title>Worked Example</title>

<p>Here is a similar worked example:</p> 
<example newNameSpace>
<p>A bag contains <m>$n</m> marbles, <m>$a</m> are purple, <m>$c</m> are rainbow, and <m>$b</m> are glow-in-the-dark. If you draw <m>$k</m> marbles
without replacement then what is the probability that you get all rainbows?</p>  
<p><em>Leave your answer as a
non-reduced fraction.</em></p>
  
<setup>
  <number name="a">8</number>
  <number name="b">3</number>
  <number name="c">7</number>
  <number name="n">18</number>
  <number name="k">4</number>
  <math name="num">nCr($c,$k)</math>
  <math name="numSimp" simplify>$num</math>
  <math name="den">nCr($n,$k)</math>
  <math name="denSimp" simplify>$den</math>
  <math name="num2" simplify>$c($c - 1)($c - 2)($c - 3)</math>
  <math name="den2" simplify>$n($n - 1)($n - 2)($n - 3)</math>
  <math name="sol">$numSimp/$denSimp</math>
  <math name="sol2">$num/$den</math>
</setup>
  
<p><em></em></p> 

<p><alert><em>Solution.</em></alert></p>
<p>First, we determine the number of possible outcomes in the sample space corresponding to choosing <m>k = $k</m> marbles from the bag of <m>n = $n</m>.</p>
<p>Since the marbles are an unordered set, we use the definition of a <ref uri="https://open.lib.umn.edu/probability/chapter/topic-1-5/">combination</ref> of <m>$k</m> marbles from a set of <m>$n</m>,
  <md>
    <mrow>C(n,k) &= \frac{n!}{k!(n - k)!}</mrow>
    <mrow>C($n,$k) &= \frac{$n!}{$k!($n - $k)!}</mrow>
    <mrow>&= $denSimp</mrow>
  </md>
So, there are <m>$denSimp</m> ways to randomly select <m>$k</m> marbles.</p>

<p>Next, we determine the number of ways to choose successfully -- to pick a rainbow marble from the bag <m>$k</m> times. This corresponds to choosing <m>k = $k</m> marbles from the subset of <m>n = $c</m> marbles which are rainbow-colored.
  <md>
    <mrow>C(n,k) &= \frac{n!}{k!(n - k)!}</mrow>
    <mrow>C($c,$k) &= \frac{$c!}{$k!($c - $k)!}</mrow>
    <mrow>&= $numSimp</mrow>
  </md>
So, there are <m>$numSimp</m> ways to randomly select <m>$k</m> rainbow marbles.</p>
    
<p>Using the basic definition of the probability of an event, 
  <md>
  <mrow>P(E) &= \frac{\text{number of outcomes in event E}}{\text{number of total outcomes}}</mrow>
  <mrow>P($k \; \text{rainbow marbles}) &= \frac{$num}{$den}</mrow>
  <mrow>&= $sol</mrow>
  <mrow>&= $sol{simplify}</mrow>
  </md>
This answer can be left unreduced, if desired.</p>
  
</example>

</hint>

<!--*********************************************
            Solution
**********************************************-->  
<solution>
<p><alert>First Solution Method:</alert> Use Combinations</p>
<p>Using the basic definition of the probability of an event, 
  <md>
  <mrow>P(E) &= \frac{\text{number of outcomes in event E}}{\text{number of total outcomes}}</mrow>
  <mrow>P($k \; \text{rainbow marbles}) &= \frac{$num}{$den}</mrow>
  <mrow>&= \frac{$numSimp}{$denSimp}</mrow>
  <mrow>&= $sol{simplify}</mrow>
  </md>
This answer can be left unreduced, if desired.</p>

<p><alert>Second Solution Method:</alert> Consider each selection independently</p>
<p>Consider the changing probabilities of each individual selection. The choices must be: (first yellow, second yellow, third yellow). Then, each choice has the following probability:</p>

<p><alert>(yellow, yellow, yellow)</alert>: At first, there are <m>$d</m> marbles to choose from, and <m>$c</m> possible yellow marbles. So, the first pick has probability <m>P = <math name="cOverD">$c/$d</math></m>. For the second pick, there are now only <math simplify>$d - 1</math> marbles left to choose from, and there are <math simplify>$c - 1</math> yellow marbles remaining. So, to pick yellow again has probability <m>P = <math name="secondChoice">(<number>$c - 1</number>)/(<number>$d - 1</number>)</math></m>. Similarly, the third choice has probability <m>P = <math name="thirdChoice">(<number>$c - 2</number>)/(<number>$d - 2</number>)</math></m>.</p>
  
<p>Combining these three selections gives a total probability for this selection of <m>P = ($cOverD)($secondChoice)($thirdChoice) = <math>(<number>$c*($c - 1)($c - 2)</number>)/(<number>$d*($d - 1)($d - 2)</number>)</math> = <math name="p1" simplify>($cOverD)($secondChoice)($thirdChoice)</math></m></p>
</solution>
</problem>
